--- !u!114 &6094929262287407616
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 158409105270474872}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: "This showcases Uli (or Uri) motifs, a traditional aesthetic practiced
      primarily by the Igbo people.\n\nOrigins in Body and Mural Art: Uli was traditionally
      a female-led art form where designs were painted onto the body for festivals
      or onto the walls of shrines and homes using natural dyes.\n\nBold Minimalism:
      Unlike many other decorative traditions, Uli is famous for its minimalist use
      of space and bold, fluid lines. It relies on \"positive\" and \"negative\"
      space to create balance.\n\nSymbolic Language: Each motif has a specific meaning,
      often drawn from nature or daily objects. For example:\n\nEke/Onwa: Representing
      the python or the moon.\n\nAnimal Prints: Like the \"Leopard\u2019s paw print\"
      or \"Tortoise\" (symbolizing wisdom and trickery).\n\nObjects: Such as the
      Ogene (gong) or Isioji (kola nut).\n\nModern Influence: In the mid-20th century,
      the \"Nsukka School\" of artists modernized Uli, moving it from the skin and
      walls onto canvas, influencing contemporary Nigerian art and design."
